Here are the essential commands to create and start working on a new project called "my-new-app":1. 
Create the Project Directory (Folder)
You'll use the mkdir command (Make Directory) to create a new folder for your project. 
It's best practice to create it inside your home folder (~) or a designated projects folder.
Bash
mkdir my-new-app


Tip: If you wanted to create a directory within a subdirectory that doesn't exist yet, you could use the -p flag (e.g., mkdir -p projects/my-new-app).2. 

Enter the Project Directory
Use the cd command (Change Directory) to move into the new folder so any files you create will be placed there.

Bash
cd my-new-app

Your prompt will likely change to show you are now inside the my-new-app directory (e.g., ~/my-new-app$).3. 

Create Basic Files
Now that you're in the folder, you can start creating the files needed for your project.
Create a README file

A README file is essential for GitHub; it describes what your project is and how to use it. 
We'll use the touch command to create the empty file.

Bash
touch README.md

Create a script or source file
For your Linux coding project, you'll likely want a shell script or a source file (like a Python or C file).

Bash
touch start.sh

4. Make Files Executable (If needed)
If start.sh is a script you intend to run, you must give it execute permissions using chmod:
Bash
chmod +x start.sh

5. View Your Setup
Use ls -l (list long format) to see your new folder structure and confirm the permissions:
Bash
ls -l

Output Example      Explanation  
-rw-rw-r--          README.md is a normal file (no execute permission).
-rwxrwxr-x          start.sh is an executable script (x).

Summary of Commands

mkdir my-new-app
cd my-new-app
touch README.md start.sh
chmod +x start.sh


whoami *Displays your current username
groups *Lists all the groups your user belongs to

