Linux Commands:
Command	  Full Meaning/Origin	                    Function & Purpose
ls	      List	                                  Lists the contents (files and directories) of the current directory.
pwd	      Print Working Directory	                Displays the absolute path of the directory you are currently in.
cd	      Change Directory	                      Navigates between directories/folders. (cd .. moves up one level, cd ~ goes to your home folder).
mkdir	    Make Directory	                        Creates a new directory (folder).
rmdir	    Remove Directory	                      Deletes an empty directory.
touch	    None (Literally "touch")	              Creates a new, empty file, or updates the last modified timestamp of an existing file.
cp	      Copy	                                  Copies files or directories from one location to another.
mv	      Move	                                  Moves files or directories, OR renames a file/directory.
rm	      Remove	                                Deletes files or directories. (Use with caution! rm -r is needed for folders).
cat	      Catenate	                              Displays the entire content of a file on the terminal screen.
less	    None (Opposite of more)	                Displays file contents one page at a time, allowing you to scroll both up and down. (Good for large files).
head	    None (Literally "head")	                Outputs the first 10 lines (by default) of a file.
tail	    None (Literally "tail")	                Outputs the last 10 lines (by default) of a file. (Often used with the -f flag to follow real-time log files).
grep	    Global Regular Expression Print	        Searches for a specific pattern of text within a file and prints the matching lines.
find	    None (Literally "find")	                Searches for files and directories based on various criteria (name, size, type, etc.)
chown	    Change Owner	                          Changes the owner and/or group of a file or directory.
chmod	    Change Mode	                            Changes the access permissions (read, write, execute) of a file or directory.
sudo	    Super User Do	                          Executes a command with elevated (administrator/root) privileges.
man	      Manual	                                Displays the official manual page for any command (e.g., man ls).
echo	    None (Literally "echo")	                Displays a line of text or variable content (often used for scripting or outputting text).
clear	    None (Literally "clear")	              Clears the entire content of the terminal screen.
df	      Disk Free	                              Displays the amount of free disk space on file systems. (Use df -h for human-readable output).
uname	    Unix Name	                              Prints system information (e.g., operating system, kernel version).

*These are simple basic commands for the Linux Terminal using your Linux with Coding

Backing Up a file

#!/bin/bash
# A simple script to back up a file by appending a timestamp.

# 1. Check if the user provided a file name (an argument)
if [ -z "$1" ]; then
    echo "Error: Please provide a filename to backup."
    echo "Usage: ./backup.sh my_file.txt"
    exit 1
fi

# 2. Assign the first argument (the file name) to a variable
FILE_TO_BACKUP=$1

# 3. Create a timestamp
TIMESTAMP=$(date +"%Y%m%d_%H%M%S")

# 4. Define the new backup file name
BACKUP_FILE="${FILE_TO_BACKUP}.${TIMESTAMP}.bak"

# 5. Copy the file
cp "$FILE_TO_BACKUP" "$BACKUP_FILE"

# 6. Print a confirmation message
echo "Successfully backed up ${FILE_TO_BACKUP} to ${BACKUP_FILE}"

Notes:
#!/bin/bash: This is called the "Shebang" line. It tells the system to run the script using the Bash shell.

$1: This refers to the first argument the user types after the script name (e.g., in ./backup.sh **file.txt**, $1 is file.txt).

if [ -z "$1" ]; then ...: Checks if the first argument is empty. If it is, it shows an error message and quits (exit 1).

date +"%Y%m%d_%H%M%S": This formats the current date and time into a neat string (e.g., 20251205_105330).

cp: The familiar copy command.

To save and exit in nano:

Press Ctrl+O (Write Out/Save).

Press Enter.

Press Ctrl+X (Exit).

Make the script executable
By default, files cannot be run as programs. We must use chmod to add the execute permission (+x):

Bash

chmod +x backup.sh

Test the script
Now, you can test it on your file.txt:

Bash

./backup.sh file.txt
You will see a confirmation message, and when you run ls -l, you will see a new file like file.txt.20251205_105330.bak!

